Generated dictionary data — licence and attribution
===================================================

Every file in this directory is generated by scripts/ingest/ from third-party
dictionary and corpus files. None of it is original to this project. It is
licensed separately from the application code, which is MIT (see /LICENSE and
/NOTICE).


LICENCE
-------

The files in this directory are made available under the Creative Commons
Attribution-ShareAlike 4.0 International licence (CC BY-SA 4.0).

    Deed:      https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/
    Full text: https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/legalcode

They are adaptations of CC BY-SA 4.0 dictionaries, so ShareAlike requires that
they carry the same licence. See the Tatoeba carve-out below — it is the one
part of this directory that is not ShareAlike upstream.


WHAT CAME FROM WHERE
--------------------

  kanji.json               KANJIDIC2 (meanings, grade, stroke counts,
                           newspaper frequency) + KRADFILE (components)
  vocab.json               JMdict (written forms, readings, English glosses,
                           part-of-speech tags, frequency bands)
  readings.json            KANJIDIC2 + JMdict (kanji readings aligned to the
                           words that anchor them)
  order.json               KANJIDIC2 + KRADFILE + JMdict (teaching order and
                           the everyday-word counts that drive it)
  components.json          KRADFILE + KANJIDIC2 (stroke counts of non-jouyou
                           components)
  confusable-derived.json  KRADFILE + KANJIDIC2 (kanji sharing a component
                           multiset and a stroke count)
  grammar-corpus.json      Tatoeba (see carve-out)
  grammar-corpus-meta.json Tatoeba (build parameters and counts)


ATTRIBUTION
-----------

JMdict
  Everyday vocabulary: written forms, readings, English glosses, and
  part-of-speech tags.
  Copyright (c) Electronic Dictionary Research and Development Group (EDRDG)
  Licence:  CC BY-SA 4.0
  Source:   https://www.edrdg.org/wiki/index.php/JMdict-EDICT_Dictionary_Project

KANJIDIC2
  Kanji meanings, on/kun readings, stroke counts, school grades, and newspaper
  frequency ranks.
  Copyright (c) Electronic Dictionary Research and Development Group (EDRDG)
  Licence:  CC BY-SA 4.0
  Source:   https://www.edrdg.org/wiki/index.php/KANJIDIC_Project

KRADFILE
  The radical decomposition each kanji is built from.
  Copyright (c) Electronic Dictionary Research and Development Group (EDRDG)
  Licence:  CC BY-SA 4.0
  Source:   https://www.edrdg.org/krad/kradinf.html

  The EDRDG licence, which covers all three files above and is the authority
  for their CC BY-SA 4.0 terms: https://www.edrdg.org/edrdg/licence.html

Tatoeba
  Example sentences and their human English translations.
  Copyright (c) The Tatoeba Project and its contributors
  Licence:  CC BY 2.0 FR
  Source:   https://tatoeba.org/eng/downloads
  Full text: https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/fr/legalcode


TATOEBA CARVE-OUT
-----------------

grammar-corpus.json and grammar-corpus-meta.json derive from Tatoeba only. No
EDRDG material is in them.

Tatoeba is CC BY 2.0 FR: attribution, no ShareAlike. Nothing here can add a
ShareAlike condition to Tatoeba's sentences, and this licence does not try to.
If you want the sentences and translations, you may take them from these files
under CC BY 2.0 FR, attributing the Tatoeba Project and its contributors.

Every sentence keeps its Tatoeba id in the `id` field, so any sentence can be
traced to its upstream entry and its author.

The selection, filtering and pattern annotations layered over those sentences
(the `n`, `v`, `p` and `sp` fields) are this project's own work, offered under
CC BY-SA 4.0 for consistency with the rest of this directory.


NOT A SOURCE
------------

The build pipeline uses fugashi and UniDic (unidic-lite) to segment and
part-of-speech-tag Japanese text. Neither is redistributed here, and the tokens
recorded in grammar-corpus.json are the surface forms of the Tatoeba sentences
themselves. UniDic is therefore a build-time tool, not a source of this data,
and is not attributed as one.
